{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/limitations-of-regression-in-scientific-formulation-of-new-equations-7f1e3c6a99a4", "time": 1683002518.255014, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/limitations-of-regression-in-scientific-formulation-of-new-equations-7f1e3c6a99a4/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Limitations of Regression. In scientific formulation of equations | by Nicolus Rotich | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Limitations of Regression", "description": "Regression analysis is a statistical technique often used to establish the relationship between the dependent or explained variable and the independent or predictors. For example, a salesman might\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/cantors-paradise/how-the-do-scientists-create-new-equations-f1059c11c0a1", "anchor_text": "how scientists formulate new equations", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://medium.com/u/22abe9089838?source=post_page-----7f1e3c6a99a4--------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Gravity Well", "paragraph_index": 3}], "all_paragraphs": ["Regression analysis is a statistical technique often used to establish the relationship between the dependent or explained variable and the independent or predictors. For example, a salesman might want to know why sales of a product, say newspaper is high on certain times of the month. He would then first try to identify the exact days or weeks, i.e. when the sales fluctuate and look for the unique happenings affecting the conversions. These findings are often followed by a decision aiming to either enhance the process or minimize the costs. Regression is therefore based on verifiable observation or experience rather than theory or pure logic, and thus sometimes referred to as empirical models.", "The most generic way of presenting a regression model is by writing the explained or response variable Y\u1d62 as a function of the independent variable(s) X\u1d62, bound by coefficients \u03b2. An extra error term, \u03f5 is usually added to represent uncaptured information that may or may not relate directly to the response variable. Whether the regression model is linear or non-linear, the equation generally follows the form below:", "The earliest forms of regression analysis was the widely known least squares introduced by Legendre in 1805, with an improved version later coming from Gauss in 1809. While regression has been bursting in glory for over three centuries now, it is marred by incredible limitations, especially when it comes to scientific publishing geared towards natural sciences.", "We recently explored how scientists formulate new equations following a methodology called RADICAL. One of the responses that I deemed carried significant weight and deserves a decent reply was from Gravity Well (see post in the screenshot below)", "This is a valid concern, and therefore we will address it along other reasons why empirical models may not be the first choice to turn to, as far as formulating new equations is of a concern.", "The first and obvious reason why regression might not work is, you are looking for totally new equations, and thus it is probable that there is no data in literature to support your hypothesis. We are therefore exploring ways to start your research even before getting to perform experiments, maybe even before getting funding to acquire the experimental setup. The following scenarios would then apply:", "While regression analysis is a great tool in analyzing observations and drawing conclusions, it can also be daunting, especially when the aim is to come up with new equations to fully describe a new scientific phenomenon. In most cases data availability is skewed, generalization and consequently cross-platform application of the derived models will be limited. Finally, we still have no access to some systems especially most cases in relativistic cosmology and contemporary quantum mechanics. As such, if a new phenomenon is to be mathematically investigated, a more robust method based on theoretical analysis becomes inevitable.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I am a Software/Algorithmic Developer, Science Writer and Systems Thinker. Most of my content is freshly distilled from up-to-date scientific journals reviews."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7f1e3c6a99a4&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Flimitations-of-regression-in-scientific-formulation-of-new-equations-7f1e3c6a99a4&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Flimitations-of-regression-in-scientific-formulation-of-new-equations-7f1e3c6a99a4&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Flimitations-of-regression-in-scientific-formulation-of-new-equations-7f1e3c6a99a4&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=logi